With a friend, we've made a mini quad-copter with clips for assembling.
It's not necessary to glu it, just "clik" it.
I put HK multistar 1704-1900 on it and a multiwii FC, the mobius and another litle cam for FPV with video transmiter.
The weight is just a litle bit more than 500grs with a 1300 mah 3S.
Post it if you make one !
The design is inspired from the Spidex Micro from Quaternium.
an alternative one on video
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oc_c7b2pTEM

Printed with 40% filling seems to be rigid enough for fly.
The frame is just good to print on a 200 x 200 bed.

1/2" NPT Male threaded holder for a foam air intake filter for small air compressors.

I dropped a box yesterday and as luck would have it i managed to snap the air intake filter off of my 5 gal pancake air compressor that was sitting on the floor below me.  My compressor is a cheap made in china unit but has served me quite well, it uses washable and reuseable foam air intake filters, the kind you wash out then lightly oil to trap dust and dirt from going into the compressor.  
Its a standard 1/2" NPT thread and i could have bought one locally to replace it but they wanted $15 for a one time use disposable filter!  So i designed a replacement to keep using the foam inserts that i already had.  If your compressor has a different type you could easily cut a piece of thick foam filter material commonly sold for AC units and layer it up for the correct thickness to create a very cheap and reuseable filter using this design.  
Print the base with support, the top just print normally without raft, unless your printer doesnt have a HBP.  
The top, aka lid, is a good snap fit into the base.  I tried one with threads but it kept vibrating out with the compressor running, the snap fit lid hasn't fell off yet.  The original design had only a few large holes, i used eight smaller holes in the lid, it doesn't restrict it too much, compressor filling time is the same, but the side effect is its much quieter with less air noise.  
Most compressors have a 1/2" NPT so this should work on many different makes and models but i wouldn't use it on anything other then the small 5 gallong or less units, the larger ones need more air flow and a larger filter.  It could easily be resized and a larger filter element made.  If you don't want to be able to wash and reuse a couple drops of super glue around the lip of the lid before assembly would make it permanent and disposable if you have and problems with the lid coming off.  Its cheap to print another!

description.text: openscad rockets by Michael Odbert
A redesign of the awesome Printrbot, in aluminum.

This is my aluminum version of the awesome Printrbot. Printrbot's open source design files and great assembly videos were instrumental in getting this guy redesigned and fabricated. --Thanks guys Most, if not all, of my design files are included here but I should note that if you intend to actually make one of these, you should probably shoot me an email. All the files have already been offset for an 1/8" endmill, and some of the layers are labeled as things that make sense to me, but maybe not someone else. There are also a few improvements that could be made --not enough to warrant the making of another one, but if you decide to take on the challenge, there are some things that could be done a bit better. This project is really intended for someone pretty well versed in the ways of the CNC... YouTube of the project can be found here:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=itZ1vlua5rg&feature=youtu.be A little more info on the design files etc can be found here:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A3XO1L11fj4 More info and a nice Picasa slideshow over at:
http://rocketbrandstudios.com (...and this is my very first Thingiverse thing... Go easy on me!)
